		<item>
			<title>A script to retain a copy of outgoing faxes</title>
			<link>http://feeds.macosxhints.com/click.phdo?i=ee3082c8385fcb3ff79f1ac282ed8c48</link>
			<pheedo:origLink>http://www.macosxhints.com/article.php?story=20081205225217399</pheedo:origLink>
			<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.macosxhints.com/article.php?story=20081205225217399</guid>
			<pubDate>Wed, 10 Dec 2008 07:30:00 -0800</pubDate>
			<comments>http://www.macosxhints.com/article.php?story=20081205225217399#comments</comments>
			<dc:subject>System 10.5</dc:subject>
			<description>For the few times I need to send a fax, I'm not going to mess with getting one of my broken third-party fax applications to run again. But the built-in OS X fax capability has some annoying limitations. One of the more annoying ones is that it doesn't save a copy of outgoing faxes. I wrote the following script as a kluge, to grab a copy of outgoing faxes and store them in /Users/Shared/Faxes/Outbox. The fax is saved (complete with the cover page) as a multi-page TIFF file.&lt;div style=&quot;margin-left: 20px; margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:10px; padding: 5px; border:1px solid; width:520px; height:120px; overflow:scroll;white-space:nowrap&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;!/bin/zshif &amp;#91; &amp;#36;EUID -ne 0 &amp;#93;; then	echo YOU MUST SUDO TO ROOT TO RUN THIS	exitfidt=`date '+%Y%m%d-%H%M%S'`t=''echo Waiting for efax to run.while &amp;#91; x&amp;#36;t = x'' &amp;#93;; do	t=`ps -ef|grep efax|grep -v grep`	sleep 1donels -al /var/spool/cups/tmpf=`echo &amp;#36;t|sed -e 's#.*&amp;#92;(/private.*&amp;#92;)#&amp;#92;1#'`if &amp;#91; -r &amp;#36;f &amp;#93;; then...&lt;br style=&quot;clear: both;&quot;/&gt;
